          <p>For the following exercises, find the specified term for the geometric sequence, given the first four terms.</p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-K7k0rwx7l9-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49446/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
          <statement>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{-1,2,-4,8,...\}.</m> Find <m>a_{12}.</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{-2,\frac{2}{3},-\frac{2}{9},\frac{2}{27},...\}.</m> Find <m>a_{7}.</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li />
              <li>
                <m>a_{7}=-\frac{2}{729}</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
  
    <exercisegroup>
        <title>Algebraic</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>For the following exercises, write the first five terms of the geometric sequence.</p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-oG736CMWlB-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49446/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
          <statement>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li>
                <m>a_{1}=-486, &amp; a_{n}=-\frac{1}{3}a_{n-1}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{1}=7, &amp; a_{n}=0.2a_{n-1}</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li />
              <li>
                <m>7,1.4,0.28,0.056,0.0112</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
  
    <exercisegroup>
        <title>Algebraic</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>For the following exercises, write a recursive formula for each geometric sequence.</p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-4EqO8WsyGK-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49446/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
          <statement>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{-1,5,-25,125,...\}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{-32,-16,-8,-4,...\}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{14,56,224,896,...\}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{10,-3,0.9,-0.27,...\}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{0.61,1.83,5.49,16.47,...\}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{\frac{3}{5},\frac{1}{10},\frac{1}{60},\frac{1}{360},...\}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{-2,\frac{4}{3},-\frac{8}{9},\frac{16}{27},...\}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{\frac{1}{512},-\frac{1}{128},\frac{1}{32},-\frac{1}{8},...\}</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li />
              <li>
                <m>a=1-32, &amp; a_{n}=\frac{1}{2}a_{n-1}</m>
              </li>
              <li />
              <li>
                <m>a_{1}=10, &amp; a_{n}=-0.3a_{n-1}</m>
              </li>
              <li />
              <li>
                <m>a_{1}=\frac{3}{5}, &amp; a_{n}=\frac{1}{6}a_{n-1}</m>
              </li>
              <li />
              <li>
                <m>a_{1}=\frac{1}{512},a_{n}=-4a_{n-1}</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
  
    <exercisegroup>
        <title>Algebraic</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>For the following exercises, write the first five terms of the geometric sequence.</p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-nKudKUdifi-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49446/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
          <statement>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=-4⋅5^{n-1}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=12⋅(-\frac{1}{2})^{n-1}</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li />
              <li>
                <m>12,-6,3,-\frac{3}{2},\frac{3}{4}</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
  
    <exercisegroup>
        <title>Algebraic</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>For the following exercises, write an explicit formula for each geometric sequence.</p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-zCE6sAfjJr-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49446/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
          <statement>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{-2,-4,-8,-16,...\}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{1,3,9,27,...\}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{-4,-12,-36,-108,...\}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{0.8,-4,20,-100,...\}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{-1.25,-5,-20,-80,...\}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{-1,-\frac{4}{5},-\frac{16}{25},-\frac{64}{125},...\}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{2,\frac{1}{3},\frac{1}{18},\frac{1}{108},...\}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{3,-1,\frac{1}{3},-\frac{1}{9},...\}</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li />
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=3^{n-1}</m>
              </li>
              <li />
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=0.8⋅(-5)^{n-1}</m>
              </li>
              <li />
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=-(\frac{4}{5})^{n-1}</m>
              </li>
              <li />
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=3⋅(-\frac{1}{3})^{n-1}</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
  
    <exercisegroup>
        <title>Algebraic</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>For the following exercises, find the specified term for the geometric sequence given.</p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-vnmP7tSQsc-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49446/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
          <statement>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li>Let <m>a_{1}=4,</m>
                <m>a_{n}=-3a_{n-1}.</m> Find <m>a_{8}.</m>
              </li>
              <li>Let <m>a_{n}=-(-\frac{1}{3})^{n-1}.</m> Find <m>a_{12}.</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li />
              <li>
                <m>a_{12}=\frac{1}{177,147}</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
  
    <exercisegroup>
        <title>Algebraic</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>For the following exercises, find the number of terms in the given finite geometric sequence.</p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-qevEGS2R04-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49446/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
          <statement>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{-1,3,-9,...,2187\}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=\{2,1,\frac{1}{2},...,\frac{1}{1024}\}</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li />
              <li>There are <m>12</m> terms in the sequence.</li>
            </ol>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
  
    <exercisegroup>
        <title>Graphical</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>For the following exercises, determine whether the graph shown represents a geometric sequence.</p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-Veooc3md6w" original="PRECALC/modules/m49446/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
          <statement>
            <image xml:id="PRECALC-GuTvCsb1XN" original="PRECALC/modules/m49446/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0" source="PRECALC/CNX_Precalc_Figure_11_03_201.jpg" width="80%">
              <description>
                               Graph of a scattered plot with labeled points: (1, -3), (2, -1), (3, 1), (4, 3), and (5, 5). The x-axis is labeled n and the y-axis is labeled a_n.
                           </description>
            </image>
          </statement>
        </exercise>
        <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-CrZUByhBah" original="PRECALC/modules/m49446/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
          <statement>
            <image xml:id="PRECALC-pcOBHZL6d6" original="PRECALC/modules/m49446/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0" source="PRECALC/CNX_Precalc_Figure_11_03_202.jpg" width="80%">
              <description>
                               Graph of a scattered plot with labeled points: (1, -0.5), (2, 0.25), (3, 1.375), (4, 3.0625), and (5, 5.5938). The x-axis is labeled n and the y-axis is labeled a_n.
                           </description>
            </image>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>The graph does not represent a geometric sequence.</p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
  
    <exercisegroup>
        <title>Graphical</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>For the following exercises, use the information provided to graph the first five terms of the geometric sequence.</p>
        </introduction>
        <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-mts08LrXMx-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49446/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
          <statement>
            <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
              <li>
                <m>a_{1}=1, &amp; r=\frac{1}{2}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{1}=3, &amp; a_{n}=2a_{n-1}</m>
              </li>
              <li>
                <m>a_{n}=27⋅0.3^{n-1}</m>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </statement>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-ZRkRIPwRpy-parts" original="PRECALC/modules/m49446/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
        <statement>
          <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
            <li>Use recursive formulas to give two examples of geometric sequences whose 3rd terms are <m>200.</m>
            </li>
            <li>Use explicit formulas to give two examples of geometric sequences whose 7th terms are <m>1024.</m>
            </li>
            <li>Find the 5th term of the geometric sequence <m>\{b,4b,16b,...\}.</m>
            </li>
            <li>Find the 7th term of the geometric sequence <m>\{64a(-b),32a(-3b),16a(-9b),...\}.</m>
            </li>
            <li>At which term does the sequence <m>\{10,12,14.4,17.28,...\}</m> exceed <m>100?</m>
            </li>
            <li>At which term does the sequence <m>\{\frac{1}{2187},\frac{1}{729},\frac{1}{243},\frac{1}{81}...\}</m> begin to have integer values?</li>
            <li>For which term does the geometric sequence <m>a_{_{n}}=-36(\frac{2}{3})^{n-1}</m> first have a non-integer value?</li>
            <li>Use the recursive formula to write a geometric sequence whose common ratio is an integer. Show the first four terms, and then find the 10th term.</li>
            <li>Use the explicit formula to write a geometric sequence whose common ratio is a decimal number between 0 and 1. Show the first 4 terms, and then find the 8th term.</li>
            <li>Is it possible for a sequence to be both arithmetic and geometric? If so, give an example.</li>
          </ol>
        </statement>
        <solution>
          <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
            <li>Answers will vary. Examples: <m>a_{1}=800, &amp; a_{n}=0.5a_{n-1}</m> and <m>a_{1}=12.5, &amp; a_{n}=4a_{n-1}</m>
            </li>
            <li />
            <li>
              <m>a_{5}=256b</m>
            </li>
            <li />
            <li>The sequence exceeds <m>100</m> at the 14th term, <m>a_{14}≈107.</m>
            </li>
            <li />
            <li>
              <m>a_{4}=-\frac{32}{3}</m> is the first non-integer value</li>
            <li />
            <li>Answers will vary. Example: Explicit formula with a decimal common ratio: <m>a_{n}=400⋅0.5^{n-1};</m> First 4 terms: <m>400,200,100,50; &amp; a_{8}=3.125</m>
            </li>
            <li />
          </ol>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-nTdM4mkliL" original="PRECALC/modules/m49447/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Try It</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>S_{20}</m> for the series <m>\text{ 1,000 + 500 + 250 + }…</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>≈2,000.00</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-xmgROQyhHP" original="PRECALC/modules/m49447/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Try It</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>∑_{k=1}^{8}3^{k}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>9,840</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-zKZmt8MyxF" original="PRECALC/modules/m49447/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Try It</title>
      <statement>
        <p>At a new job, an employee’s starting salary is $32,100. She receives a 2% annual raise. How much will she have earned by the end of 8 years?</p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>$275,513.31</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-7SrpeIcY0o" original="PRECALC/modules/m49447/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Try It</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\frac{1}{3}+\frac{1}{2}+\frac{3}{4}+\frac{9}{8}+...</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>The sum is not defined.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-VQJoOaPKuf" original="PRECALC/modules/m49447/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Try It</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>24+(−12)+6+(−3)+...</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>The sum of the infinite series is defined.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-61tJBi32Ue" original="PRECALC/modules/m49447/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Try It</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>∑_{k=1}^{∞}15⋅(-0.3)^{k}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>The sum of the infinite series is defined.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-SczHn3bYn2" original="PRECALC/modules/m49447/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Try It</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>2+\frac{2}{3}+\frac{2}{9}+...</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>3</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-t6Oa1OfUqO" original="PRECALC/modules/m49447/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Try It</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>∑_{k=1}^{∞}0.76k+1</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>The series is not geometric.</p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  
    <exercise xml:id="PRECALC-meLR6I9hhi" original="PRECALC/modules/m49447/index.cnxml" license="CC-BY-4.0">
      <title>Try It</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>∑_{k=1}^{∞}(-\frac{3}{8})^{k}</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>-\frac{3}{11}</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </exercise>
  
  </exercises>

  <!-- END BORROWED CONTENT -->

